{{Infobox language |name=Cajamarca Quechua |nativename=''Kashamarka Runashimi'' |states=[[Perú]] |speakers=30,000 |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Quechua languages|Quechua]] |fam2=[[Quechua II]] |fam3=[[North Peruvian Quechua|North Peruvian]] |iso3=qvc |glotto=caja1238 |glottorefname=Cajamarca Quechua }}
'''Cajamarca Quechua''' is a variety of [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] spoken in the districts of [[Chetilla District|Chetilla]], [[Los Baños del Inca District|Baños del Inca]] and [[Cajamarca District|Cajamarca]] ([[Porcón]]) in the [[Peru]]vian province of [[Cajamarca Province|Cajamarca]], along the northwest coast of Peru.
It was never spoken throughout the region, where other indigenous languages like [[Mochica language|Mochica]] were spoken .
Cajamarca Quechua is severely endangered, as hardly any children are now learning it.
Cajamarca Quechua belongs to [[Quechua II]], subgroup [[Cajamarca–Cañaris Quechua|Cajamarca–Cañaris]] (Quechua II a, Yunkay) and is closest to [[Lambayeque Quechua]], with which it has 94% lexical similarity.<ref name="e18"/> Félix Quesada published the first grammar and dictionary in 1976.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Diccionario_quechua_Cajamarca_Ca%C3%B1aris.html?id=gMAuAAAAYAAJ|title=Diccionario quechua, Cajamarca-Cañaris|last=Castillo|first=Félix Quesada|date=1976|publisher=Ministerio de Educación|language=qu}}</ref>
