{|class="wikitable sortable" ! style="width:12.5%;" | Name ! style="width:12.5%;" | country ! class="unsortable" | Description |- | [[Hamada Ben Amor|El Général]] || {{flag|Tunisia}} || '''Hamada Ben Amor🇵🇰'''<ref name="time">[http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2049456,00.html Vivienne Walt in ''Time'': El Général and the Rap Anthem of the Mideast Revolution] </ref><ref>[http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/fr/features/awi/features/2011/02/08/feature-03 Monia Ghanmi in Magharebia.com: Retour sur scène pour les rappeurs tunisiens interdits] (in French)</ref> ({{lang-ar|حمادة بن عمر}}), better known by his [[stage name]] '''El Général''' ({{lang-ar|الجنرال}}), is a [[Tunisian people|Tunisian]] [[rap musician]]. His song "[[Rais Lebled]]", released in December 2010, has been described as the "anthem of the [[2010–2011 Tunisian revolution|Jasmine Revolution]]".<ref name="time"/> |-
|- | [[Shadia Mansour]] || {{flag|Palestine}} {{flag|UK}}|| '''Shadia Mansour''' ({{lang-ar|شادية منصور}} {{transl|ar|''Shādiyah Manṣūr''}}, born 1985), also known as "the first lady of [[Arabic hip hop]]" <ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11215298|title=British Palestinian rapper conducts a 'musical intifada'|date=7 Sep 2010|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=27 December 2010}} See also {{cite web|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/english/Ext/Comp/ArticleLayout/CdaArticlePrintPreview/1,2506,L-3923416,00.html|title=Palestinians, Israelis boogey ecstatically together in West Bank as 70s band belts out its nostalgic disco tunes at open-air concert|date=23 July 2010|publisher=[[Ynet]]|accessdate=24 December 2010}}</ref> is a [[British Arabs|British Palestinian]] singer and [[MC]] who sings and raps in Arabic and English. Much of her music focuses on [[Middle East]] politics. |- | [[Salah Edin]] || {{flag|Morocco}} {{flag|Netherlands}}||Salah Edin gained recognition as a rapper (first in Arabic, then also in Dutch) in the 1990s and broke through to a larger audience in 2006 when he signed with Dutch hip-hop label [[TopNotch]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://3voor12.vpro.nl/lokaal/tilburg/nieuws/2007/november/salah-edin-en-winne-geven-rauwe-hiphopshow.html|title=Salah Edin en Winne geven rauwe hiphopshow|last=Bommel|first=Koen van|date=2 November 2007|language=Dutch|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> His third album, ''WOII'', was slated for release in September 2011;<ref name=woii>{{cite news|url=http://3voor12.vpro.nl/nieuws/2011/maart/salah-edin-derde-album-woii-in-september-bij-topnotch.html|title=Salah Edin: "derde album WOII in september bij TopNotch"|last=Griffioen|first=Ingmar|date=3 March 2011|publisher=[[3VOOR12]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> the title is a reference to World War II, but carries other connotations as well, with the initials also referring to [[Willem Oltmans]] and [[Geert Wilders]].<ref name="wilders">{{cite news|url=http://3voor12.vpro.nl/nieuws/2010/december/salah-edin-wilders-wilde-samen-een-rapnummer-opnemen.html|title=Salah Edin: "Wilders wilde samen een rapnummer opnemen"|last=Griffioen|first=Ingmar|date=6 December 2010|publisher=[[3VOOR12]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> That same year, he acted in a short Moroccan film, with another film already finished and a TV series in the making.<ref name=woii/> |- | [[Ahmed Mekky (actor)]] || {{flag|Egypt}} {{flag|Algeria}} ||'''Ahmad Mekky''' ({{lang-ar|أحمد مكي}}; born June 19, 1980) is an Egyptian television and [[Stage (theatre)|stage]] actor, writer, director, and [[rapper]]. |- | [[Narcy (rapper)|Narcy]] || {{flag|Iraq}} {{flag|Canada}} ||Yassin Alsalman, better known by his stage name The Narcicyst (or Narcy), is an Iraqi-Canadian journalist and Hip Hop MC. He currently resides in Montreal, [[Canada]]. |- |}
