All official [[holiday]]s in [[Estonia]] are established by acts of [[Parliament of Estonia|Parliament]].
==Public holidays== The following are holidays that mean days off: {| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 100%; width="100% |- style="background: #ececec;" ! width="110px"|Date ! width="240px"|English Name ! width="170px"|Estonian Name ! width="565px"|Remarks |- | January 1 | [[New Year|New Year's Day]] | ''uusaasta'' | |- | February 24 | [[Independence Day (Estonia)|Independence Day]] | ''iseseisvuspäev'' | '''[[National Day]]''' – celebrates the [[Estonian Declaration of Independence|declaration of independence]] in 1918. |- | ''[[Moveable feast|Moveable]] Friday'' | [[Good Friday]] | ''suur reede'' | |- | ''Moveable Sunday'' | [[Easter Sunday]] | ''ülestõusmispühade 1. püha'' | Commonly known as ''lihavõtted''. |- | May 1 | [[May Day|Spring Day (May Day)]] | ''kevadpüha'' | |- | ''Moveable'' | [[Pentecost|Whitsunday (Pentecost)]] | ''nelipühade 1. püha'' | |- | June 23 | [[Victory Day]] | ''võidupüha'' and ''jaanilaupäev'' | Celebrates the victory in the [[Battle of Cēsis (1919)|Battle of Võnnu]] during the [[Estonian War of Independence]]. |- | June 24 | [[Jaanipäev|Jaan's Day]] or [[Midsummer Day#Estonia|Midsummer Day]] or [[St John's Day (Estonia)|St. John's Day]] | ''jaanipäev'' | [[Jaaniõhtu]] is celebrated in the night before Midsummer Day. |- | August 20 | [[Estonian Sovereignty Declaration|Day of Restoration of Independence]] | ''taasiseseisvumispäev'' | Celebrates Estonia's [[Estonia#Return to Independence|restoration of independence]] in 1991. |- | December 24 | [[Christmas Eve]] | ''jõululaupäev'' | |- | December 25 | [[Christmas Day]] | ''esimene jõulupüha'' | |- | December 26 | [[Boxing Day]] | ''teine jõulupüha'' | |}
==National Holidays== The following holidays do not give a day off: {| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 100%; width="100% |- style="background: #ececec;" ! width="110px"|Date ! width="240px"|English Name ! width="170px"|Estonian Name ! width="565px"|Remarks |- | January 6 | [[Epiphany (holiday)|The Epiphany]] | ''kolmekuningapäev'' | |- | February 2 | Anniversary of the [[Treaty of Tartu (Russian–Estonian)|Tartu Peace Treaty]] | ''Tartu rahulepingu aastapäev'' | Treaty that ended the [[Estonian War of Independence]] |- | March 14 | Native Language Day | ''emakeelepäev'' | [[Kristjan Jaak Peterson]]'s birthday. |- | ''Moveable Sunday'' | [[Mothers' Day]] | ''emadepäev'' | Held on the second Sunday of May. |- | June 4 | [[National Flag Day]] | ''Eesti lipu päev'' | Date when the [[Flag of Estonia]] was first consecrated in 1884. |- | June 14 | [[National day of mourning|Day of Mourning and Commemoration]] | ''leinapäev'' | Commemorating the victims of [[Soviet deportations from Estonia|Soviet deportations]] in 1941 and 1949. |- | August 23 | [[European Day of Remembrance for Victims of Stalinism and Nazism]] | ''kommunismi ja natsismi ohvrite mälestuspäev'' | Day when the [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]] was signed in 1939. |- | ''Moveable Sunday'' | [[National Grandparents Day|Grandparents Day]] | ''vanavanemate päev'' | Held on the second Sunday of September. |- | September 22 | [[Resistance during World War II|Resistance Fighting]] Day | ''vastupanuvõitluse päev'' | [[Otto Tief]]'s attempt to [[National Committee of the Republic of Estonia|restore the Estonian independence]] in 1944 |- |October 1 |[[Local government]] Day |''omavalitsuspäev'' | |- | November 2 | [[All Souls' Day]] | ''hingedepäev'' | |- | ''Moveable Sunday'' | [[Fathers' Day]] | ''isadepäev'' | Held on the second Sunday of November. |- | November 16 | [[Independence Day|Day of Declaration of Sovereignty]] | ''taassünni päev'' | [[Estonian Sovereignty Declaration|Estonian Declaration of Sovereignty]], which was issued in 1988. |}
